         <entryFree xml:id="k000145" type="architectural feature">
            <term xml:id="term-k000145-1" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin-nt" type="preferred">danchi</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000145-2" xml:lang="zh-Hant">丹墀</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000145-3" xml:lang="zh-Hans">丹墀</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000145-4" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin">dānchí</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000145-5" xml:lang="zh-latn-wadegile">tan-ch'ih</term>
            <note type="Gloss">
               <p xml:lan="en" source="biblk000145-1">Danchi generally refers to the ground of the main building in the palace complex, originated from painting the floor with cinnabar(丹砂) in the Han Dynasty palaces.
                  In the Han dynasty (202BCE-220CE), it refers to the ground inside the palace. After the Tang (618-907) and Song Dynasties (960-1279), danchi is usually related to a lutai (露臺), but its exact position changes with time. In the Northern Song Dynasty (960-1127), danchi refers to the upper ground of the lutai outside the palace. In the Ming (1368-1644) and Qing Dynasties (1644-1911), it relates to the ground under the lutai outside a palace and sometimes used in the Confucian temple(文廟), yashu(衙署) and other structures.
               </p>
            </note>
